Why would a beautiful woman want to tattoo all over her body and make it ugly?

Many reasons but let us assume some.

A woman who isn’t available to put on a pedestal for someone else’s fantasies to project it all on her.

If as you see it, a skin, her body is a representation of the woman you saw and she has made a decision to have that skin inked in, she probably telling herself these following words….

  • This is my body
  • This is my life
  • This is my choice
  • I will live with the choices I make
  • This is my standard of attractiveness
  • This is what beauty is to me
  • It is not anyone else’s standard but my own and I don’t need anyone’s approval or care what anyone else thinks is attractive.
  • In other words, I say what beauty is to me and no one else.

That is her path, her journey, her story, her sky and her ground.

So anyone else’s opinion doesn’t come into the equation of what they think is attractive or not.

And that’s the point - it’s her life and what matters is what is important to her and not someone else.

Someone else will see her beautiful.

She isn’t that concerned about anyone who else who judges on whether she is beautiful or ugly.

I am attracted to women who have tattoos and who are very sexually confident to experiement and explore. I find them exciting, fun, intelligent, incredibly bright and most of all, they are so not following the crowd, and get me more than most women ever do.

So I do get attracted to women who have tattoos and always wanted to know the story behind the creative work on their body. Some stories have deep meaning withn layers of stories.

Personally, ugly for me is someone looking at someone and trying to project their own ideals and values which defines them not the person they are looking at.

Most of all, it only takes asking then person about their tattoo and they’d probably have an amazing conversation.

There might be a history to it.

A story,

A meaning.

But we will never know, because if all we are doing is nit picking on what is beautiful and what isn’t, rather than getting to know someone, then we will never know the person.

All we see is our own perception, insecurities, ideals, values and our own reality. What we see defines us far more than it defines who we are looking at.

We can be busy looking at perceived value rather than absolute value.

And absolute value is locked inside of the person and only shared to someone who gives time to respect that person’s decisions, gets to know the person and nurtures the connection.

Of course, it is all assumptions on why she has tattoos all over her body.

That’s an answer we won’t know because who else knows except her. Therefore, there is no point asking everyone else who don’t even know her. All we will say will come from our own reality not her reality.
